{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Frame Consistency Problem"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A video diffusion model denoises frames inside a shared latent space, but the denoising objective is still fundamentally a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "per-frame prediction problem"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": the model predicts the noise (or velocity) for each spatial position at each timestep. Without an explicit mechanism that forces adjacent frames to agree on object identities, colours, and geometry, small independent sampling errors accumulate into visible "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "temporal flickering"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " — the same face subtly changes between frames, background colours shift, or fine texture patterns strobelight."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Three root causes compound the problem:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Independent denoising"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": when frames are denoised in a standard 2-D U-Net independently, they share no memory of each other beyond what the text prompt and their shared noise initialisation supply."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "High CFG amplifies drift"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": classifier-free guidance extrapolates the score function away from the unconditional direction. At high guidance scales the per-frame extrapolation errors grow larger and become visible as flicker. Video models therefore use lower guidance (6–9) than typical image models (7.5–15)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "No explicit 3-D scene representation"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": the model must infer occlusion, camera movement, and object re-appearance from 2-D supervision alone. When an object exits and re-enters frame its appearance can change because there is no persistent 3-D buffer holding the ground truth."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Frame consistency causes (left) and mitigation strategies plus AnimateDiff motion module architecture (right/bottom)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mitigation 1: Temporal Attention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The canonical architectural fix is to add a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "temporal attention layer"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " after each spatial block in the U-Net. Each frame's feature map attends over the corresponding spatial position in all other frames. This gives every frame a global view of the clip's temporal context before the spatial convolution refines it locally."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\nclass TemporalCrossFrameAttention(nn.Module):\n    \"\"\"\n    Per-position temporal attention across F frames.\n    Operates on feature maps of shape (B*F, C, H, W).\n    \"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, channels, num_heads=8):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.num_heads = num_heads\n        self.head_dim = channels // num_heads\n        self.qkv = nn.Linear(channels, channels * 3)\n        self.proj = nn.Linear(channels, channels)\n        self.norm = nn.LayerNorm(channels)\n\n    def forward(self, x, num_frames):\n        # x: (B*F, C, H, W)\n        BF, C, H, W = x.shape\n        B = BF // num_frames\n        F = num_frames\n\n        # Flatten spatial: (B*F, C, H*W) → (B, H*W, F, C) → (B*H*W, F, C)\n        x_flat = x.flatten(2).permute(0, 2, 1)          # (B*F, H*W, C)\n        x_flat = x_flat.reshape(B, F, H * W, C)\n        x_flat = x_flat.permute(0, 2, 1, 3)             # (B, H*W, F, C)\n        x_flat = x_flat.reshape(B * H * W, F, C)\n\n        # Standard multi-head self-attention over the frame axis\n        residual = x_flat\n        x_flat = self.norm(x_flat)\n        qkv = self.qkv(x_flat).chunk(3, dim=-1)         # each: (B*H*W, F, C)\n        q, k, v = qkv\n\n        # Reshape for multi-head: (B*H*W, num_heads, F, head_dim)\n        def reshape_heads(t):\n            return t.reshape(B * H * W, F, self.num_heads, self.head_dim).permute(0, 2, 1, 3)\n\n        q, k, v = reshape_heads(q), reshape_heads(k), reshape_heads(v)\n        scale = self.head_dim ** -0.5\n        attn = (q @ k.transpose(-2, -1)) * scale          # (B*H*W, heads, F, F)\n        attn = F.softmax(attn, dim=-1)\n        out = (attn @ v)                                   # (B*H*W, heads, F, head_dim)\n        out = out.permute(0, 2, 1, 3).reshape(B * H * W, F, C)\n        out = self.proj(out) + residual\n\n        # Reshape back to (B*F, C, H, W)\n        out = out.reshape(B, H * W, F, C).permute(0, 2, 1, 3)  # (B, F, H*W, C)\n        out = out.reshape(B * F, H * W, C).permute(0, 2, 1)    # (B*F, C, H*W)\n        return out.reshape(BF, C, H, W)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mitigation 2: Shared Noise Initialisation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A deceptively simple trick with a large empirical effect: initialise all frames from the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "same"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " random noise tensor rather than independent per-frame noise. Low-frequency structure (background colours, lighting, global layout) is then shared from the very start of denoising. A blended strategy — some shared, some independent — gives the best balance between consistency and motion diversity:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\n\ndef shared_noise_init(\n    batch_size: int,\n    num_frames: int,\n    channels: int,\n    height: int,\n    width: int,\n    alpha: float = 0.5,          # fraction of shared noise\n    device: str = \"cuda\",\n    generator: torch.Generator | None = None,\n) -> torch.Tensor:\n    \"\"\"\n    Returns latent noise of shape (B, F, C, H, W).\n    alpha=1.0 → all frames share the same noise (maximum consistency, zero motion diversity).\n    alpha=0.0 → fully independent per-frame noise (SVD default behaviour).\n    alpha=0.5 → blended; empirically good for 16-frame clips.\n    \"\"\"\n    shape = (batch_size, channels, height, width)\n    shared = torch.randn(shape, generator=generator, device=device)   # (B, C, H, W)\n    # Expand shared noise across all frames\n    shared_expanded = shared.unsqueeze(1).expand(-1, num_frames, -1, -1, -1)  # (B, F, C, H, W)\n    # Independent per-frame noise\n    independent = torch.randn(\n        (batch_size, num_frames, channels, height, width),\n        generator=generator, device=device\n    )\n    return alpha * shared_expanded + (1 - alpha) * independent\n\n# Usage in a diffusion pipeline (schematic)\nlatents = shared_noise_init(batch_size=1, num_frames=16,\n                            channels=4, height=64, width=64,\n                            alpha=0.5)\n# latents shape: (1, 16, 4, 64, 64)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mitigation 3: AnimateDiff Motion Modules"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "AnimateDiff (Guo et al. 2023) packages temporal attention into a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "plug-in motion module"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " that can be inserted into any Stable Diffusion 1.x or SDXL U-Net without modifying the original spatial weights. This design has two benefits: the SD weights retain all their learned image priors, and any existing image LoRA or ControlNet adaptor works unchanged."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The motion module is trained on WebVid-10M (video-caption pairs) while the SD weights are fully frozen. Only the temporal attention parameters are updated, so the module learns to correlate frames without disturbing spatial fidelity."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install diffusers transformers accelerate\nfrom diffusers import AnimateDiffPipeline, MotionAdapter, EulerDiscreteScheduler\nfrom diffusers.utils import export_to_gif\nimport torch\n\n# Load the motion adapter (trained temporal attention weights)\nadapter = MotionAdapter.from_pretrained(\n    \"guoyww/animatediff-motion-adapter-v1-5-2\",\n    torch_dtype=torch.float16,\n)\n\n# Combine with any SD1.5-compatible base model\npipe = AnimateDiffPipeline.from_pretrained(\n    \"runwayml/stable-diffusion-v1-5\",\n    motion_adapter=adapter,\n    torch_dtype=torch.float16,\n)\npipe.scheduler = EulerDiscreteScheduler.from_config(\n    pipe.scheduler.config,\n    beta_schedule=\"linear\",\n)\npipe.enable_vae_slicing()          # reduce VRAM\npipe.to(\"cuda\")\n\noutput = pipe(\n    prompt=\"a golden retriever running through autumn leaves, cinematic\",\n    negative_prompt=\"blurry, low quality, jitter, flicker\",\n    num_frames=16,\n    guidance_scale=7.5,\n    num_inference_steps=25,\n    generator=torch.Generator(\"cuda\").manual_seed(42),\n)\nframes = output.frames[0]          # list of 16 PIL images\nexport_to_gif(frames, \"animatediff_output.gif\")\nprint(f\"{len(frames)} frames exported\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Loading a LoRA Alongside AnimateDiff"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Because the SD backbone is untouched, character-specific LoRAs compose with the motion module directly:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# After creating the AnimateDiffPipeline above:\npipe.load_lora_weights(\n    \"path/or/hf_repo\",\n    weight_name=\"my_character.safetensors\",\n    adapter_name=\"character_lora\",\n)\npipe.set_adapters([\"character_lora\"], adapter_weights=[0.8])\n# Now the generated video uses the LoRA character style\n# while AnimateDiff's motion module ensures temporal consistency."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mitigation 4: FLATTEN and Optical Flow Guidance"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "FLATTEN (2024) shows that optical flow consistency can be injected at inference time with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "zero additional training"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". During denoising, it computes optical flow between adjacent predicted-clean-frame estimates (using RAFT or similar), warps the previous frame's features to the current frame's coordinate system, and blends them:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Schematic — uses torchvision's RAFT for optical flow\n# pip install torchvision\nimport torch\nfrom torchvision.models.optical_flow import raft_large, Raft_Large_Weights\nfrom torchvision.transforms.functional import resize\n\n@torch.no_grad()\ndef flatten_warp(frames_pred: torch.Tensor, blend_alpha: float = 0.5) -> torch.Tensor:\n    \"\"\"\n    frames_pred: (F, 3, H, W) float32 predicted-clean frames in [0,1]\n    Returns flow-warped and blended frames.\n    \"\"\"\n    weights = Raft_Large_Weights.DEFAULT\n    raft = raft_large(weights=weights).eval()\n    transforms = weights.transforms()\n\n    out = [frames_pred[0]]\n    for i in range(1, len(frames_pred)):\n        prev = (frames_pred[i - 1] * 255).to(torch.uint8)\n        curr = (frames_pred[i]     * 255).to(torch.uint8)\n        # RAFT expects (1, 3, H, W) uint8\n        flow = raft(prev.unsqueeze(0), curr.unsqueeze(0))[-1]  # (1, 2, H, W)\n        # Warp previous frame to current frame coordinates\n        warped = warp_with_flow(out[-1], flow.squeeze(0))       # (3, H, W)\n        blended = blend_alpha * warped + (1 - blend_alpha) * frames_pred[i]\n        out.append(blended)\n    return torch.stack(out)\n\n\ndef warp_with_flow(frame: torch.Tensor, flow: torch.Tensor) -> torch.Tensor:\n    \"\"\"Bilinear warp of frame (3,H,W) using flow (2,H,W).\"\"\"\n    _, H, W = frame.shape\n    grid_y, grid_x = torch.meshgrid(\n        torch.arange(H, dtype=torch.float32),\n        torch.arange(W, dtype=torch.float32),\n        indexing=\"ij\",\n    )\n    new_x = (grid_x + flow[0]) / (W - 1) * 2 - 1\n    new_y = (grid_y + flow[1]) / (H - 1) * 2 - 1\n    grid = torch.stack([new_x, new_y], dim=-1).unsqueeze(0)  # (1, H, W, 2)\n    return torch.nn.functional.grid_sample(\n        frame.unsqueeze(0), grid, align_corners=True\n    ).squeeze(0)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Measuring Temporal Consistency"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The standard metric is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "CLIP Temporal Consistency"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (sometimes called CLIP-T or warping error). It computes the average CLIP cosine similarity between consecutive frame pairs — higher means more consistent:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install open-clip-torch\nimport open_clip\nimport torch\nfrom PIL import Image\nfrom torchvision import transforms\n\ndef clip_temporal_consistency(frames: list[Image.Image], model_name: str = \"ViT-L-14\") -> float:\n    \"\"\"\n    frames: list of PIL images (one per frame), at least 2 frames.\n    Returns mean CLIP cosine similarity between adjacent frame pairs (higher = more consistent).\n    \"\"\"\n    model, _, preprocess = open_clip.create_model_and_transforms(\n        model_name, pretrained=\"openai\"\n    )\n    model.eval()\n    device = \"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\"\n    model.to(device)\n\n    embeddings = []\n    with torch.no_grad(), torch.autocast(device):\n        for frame in frames:\n            img_t = preprocess(frame).unsqueeze(0).to(device)\n            emb = model.encode_image(img_t)\n            emb = emb / emb.norm(dim=-1, keepdim=True)  # ℓ2 normalise\n            embeddings.append(emb)\n\n    sims = []\n    for i in range(len(embeddings) - 1):\n        sim = (embeddings[i] * embeddings[i + 1]).sum(dim=-1).item()\n        sims.append(sim)\n    return sum(sims) / len(sims)   # mean pairwise CLIP cosine similarity\n\n# Typical values:\n# Real video clips:          ~0.985\n# Good video model output:   ~0.975–0.982\n# Naive frame-by-frame gen:  ~0.940–0.960"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A complementary metric is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "warping error"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " — the per-pixel L1 error between frame "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "t"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and the optical-flow warp of frame "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "t-1"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " into frame "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "t"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "'s coordinate system. Lower warping error indicates the model correctly predicts motion."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Long-Video Consistency: Sliding Window Strategies"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Most video models generate 16–49 frames per call. Longer videos are built by "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "overlapping sliding windows"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " where the last N frames of one window seed (or condition) the next window. Without this seeding, consecutive segments are visually independent and the video looks like unrelated clips spliced together."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from diffusers import AnimateDiffPipeline\nfrom diffusers.utils import export_to_gif\nimport torch\nfrom PIL import Image\n\ndef generate_long_video(\n    pipe: AnimateDiffPipeline,\n    prompt: str,\n    total_frames: int = 64,\n    window_size: int = 16,\n    overlap: int = 4,           # frames reused from previous window as conditioning\n    **kwargs,\n) -> list[Image.Image]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Stitches multiple AnimateDiff windows with overlapping frame conditioning.\n    overlap frames from the previous window are passed as initial frames to the next.\n    \"\"\"\n    all_frames: list[Image.Image] = []\n    context_frames: list[Image.Image] = []\n\n    stride = window_size - overlap\n    num_windows = max(1, (total_frames - overlap + stride - 1) // stride)\n\n    for win_idx in range(num_windows):\n        # On subsequent windows, prepend the last `overlap` generated frames\n        if context_frames:\n            # Use last `overlap` frames as the latent seed via img2img approach\n            # For AnimateDiff, inject them as first frames via conditioning mask\n            init_frames = context_frames[-overlap:]\n        else:\n            init_frames = []\n\n        frames_needed = min(window_size, total_frames - len(all_frames) + overlap)\n        result = pipe(\n            prompt=prompt,\n            num_frames=frames_needed,\n            **kwargs,\n        ).frames[0]\n\n        new_frames = result[overlap:] if context_frames else result\n        all_frames.extend(new_frames)\n        context_frames = result\n\n        if len(all_frames) >= total_frames:\n            break\n\n    return all_frames[:total_frames]\n\n# Export stitched long video\n# frames = generate_long_video(pipe, \"A sunset timelapse\", total_frames=48)\n# export_to_gif(frames, \"long_video.gif\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Comparison of Consistency Strategies"
          }
        ]
      },
